long-description.p: The village of Garristown is recorded in the civil survey of 1654. There was a medieval church on the site of the now former Church of Ireland. The current street pattern can be discerned in Rocques map of 1746 and it is probable that the settlement dates from before that, possibly the late 16th or early 17th century. The development of the village has been slow and measured partly due its rural location and partly due to population decline over the last 150 years. The old RIC barracks, located in the centre of the village is indicative of the importance of the village as an administrative centre for the northwestern part of the county in the early part of last century.
